@david-de2 if you really want to receive data from your websocket, you can use a custom subscriber http://django-websocket-redis.readthedocs.org/en/latest/installation.html?highlight=subscriber .
This is quite dangerous as you have to make sure to wrap any custom code in a try/catch but "all you have to do" is override `publish_message` with something like that

```python
class MySubscriber(RedisSubscriber):
    def publish_message(self, message, expire=None):
        try:
            # custom code goes here
        catch Exception:
            # I mean it, catch everything, log it if needed but do catch everything
            pass
        return super(MySubscriber, self).publish_message(message, expire)
```

Keep in mind that your custom also has the potential to considerably slow down your websocket so don't do any heavy lifting there. Creating a celery task might be your best option here.

