@ksachs can you detail what issue you are currently having with the example in JSON? Maybe it just suffices that we explain you some usage pattern we are employing with JSON and we can move on. Otherwise, there is really no further way in which this can be simplified.

e.g.: 
```json
"self": {
        "$ref": "http://labs.inspirehep.net/record/1110315"
},
```

is simply something that needs to be there to have a URL to refer to the record itself.

```json
{
        "curated_relation": true,
        "record": {
            "$ref": "http://labs.inspirehep.net/record/D0_COLLAB_RECID"
        },
        "value": "D0"
},
```
is a recurrent pattern in order to link an other record. The `value` is the actual identifier chosen from the referred record, `record.$ref` is the actual pointer, and `curated_relation` is there to signify if a curator actually prof-checked the relation (or it is surely correct, e.g. if we match an author profile via an ORCID).

Any other things that are not clear?

> NextMarker may not be populated, use the last object seen if this is the case.

All recursive cases need to handle this since we won't have the NextMarker available. Here is the sample implementation in golang library 

~~~
  switch {
        case recursive == true:
                var marker string
                for {
                        result, err := a.listObjects(bucket, marker, prefix, "", 1000)
                        if err != nil {
                                ch <- ObjectStatCh{
                                        Stat: ObjectStat{},
                                        Err:  err,
                                }
                                return
                        }
                        for _, object := range result.Contents {
                                ch <- ObjectStatCh{
                                        Stat: object,
                                        Err:  nil,
                                }
                                marker = object.Key                <<<-------- Right here 
                        }
                        if !result.IsTruncated {
                                break
                        }
                }
~~~ 

In-fact for a delimited case we don't need to handle NextMarker since we are going to be printing 1000 at a time anyways and traversing through delimiter is based on prefix so we are good.

