@yzou It seems that, before #803, logging of wrong password was handled by [this line](https://github.com/shadowsocks/shadowsocks/blob/e332ec93e9c90f1cbee676b022bf2c5d5b7b1239/shadowsocks/tcprelay.py#L415), and #803 broke the flow. It is, in my humble opinion, more maintainable if you would follow the original logic, instead of writing your own new exception handling, unless there are other issues that prevent you to do so.
And of course I could just change the log msg (and have guaranteed success, because fail2ban use RegEx to capture log msg), but again, the code quality and maintainability suffer. Sooner or later, the code would become unmanageable as the codebase grows.

And btw, you must realize how many failed authentication attempts are going on. It's not in any way less than your ssh port. An extra layer of protection is never a bad idea, and **[it _was_ designed](/shadowsocks/shadowsocks/wiki/Securing-Public-Shadowsocks-Server) to [behave this way](/shadowsocks/shadowsocks/wiki/Ban-Brute-Force-Crackers)**.

