@delcypher Z3 is not a new project, we have lots of users that use older systems. So far 5 years back was my limit, which is a "usual" timeframe for a PhD. Also, remember the VS is not free (or most of it wasn't, until recently), some universities may not have licenses for the latest cutting-edge VS, and some users can't upgrade because of other project dependencies, or because the upgrade would take too much testing effort (e.g. one MSFT product group that ships three different versions of libz3.dll for different sub-projects...). And yes, those projects will have to face becoming irrelevant, but that is not our call. 

@NikolajBjorner Yes, that when it's 5 years. What sort of inadvert regressions are you hinting at?

In general, my attitude is to maintain backwards compatibility if it's free and this is one of those cases (or at least it is until someone has run some benchmarks...). There is no point in breaking something and interrupting other people's work, just for the sake of pretending to be "cool" by using the latest crazy language features and similar.

